  <scopecontent encodinganalog="520"> 
	 <head>Scope and Content Note</head> 
	 <p>Chiefly correspondence between Richard Sparks and a variety of people,
		mainly from the 1930s, about the proper treatment of gorillas. Of particular
		concern is the well-being of Ngagi, Mbongo, and Okere, captured by author
		Martin Johnson in the Belgian Congo, in 1931. Sparks advocates for their
		scientific study in a zoo rather than becoming a circus sideshow. Chief
		correspondents are: Mary L. Jobe Akeley, naturalist associated with the
		American Museum of Natural History; Belle J. Benchley, manager of the
		Zoological Society of San Diego; and Harold C. Bingham, psychobiologist in the
		study of gorilla behavior. Other correspondence, magazine articles, and
		black-and-white photographs are concerned with Congo, a gorilla brought from
		the Belgian Congo in 1925 by author Ben Burbridge, and studied by Yale
		University researcher Robert M. Yerkes. Miscellaneous material relates to Carl
		Akeley's animal sculptures, Theodore Spicer-Simson's medallic art, and other
		gorillas in captivity.</p> 
  </scopecontent> 
